In part one of this series we walked through using Docker to containerize a simple Node.js app and verified our shiny new container worked as expected. Unfortunately, containers aren&rsquo;t much use if we can&rsquo;t get them deployed to start delighting users with the sheer awesomeness of our brilliant code.
In the container world, the path to production involves some sort of registry&hellip; While it sounds fancy, a registry isn&rsquo;t much different from the simple web servers you historically used to host RPMs or DEBs (essentially just another tool to help you maintain the ITIL concept of a Definitive Software Library.
